<subSubSection id="0513B284509986E8D361E0D96283C98C" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="29A3F10D2C95852B76EDC0A27DF783EB" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
According to Jacot (1933, p. 239) 
<taxonomicName id="5EB46A4678291168AAC77DED3B1DC0E1" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Hoplophthiracarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hoplophthiracarus</taxonomicName>
is recognizable by the following characters. The anal covers are not convex as in 
<taxonomicName id="7FB21775B5443B863485F6C86868CCC3" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Steganacarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Steganacarus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D820D8EAA440797923EBA9FC612E316F" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Hoplophorella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hoplophorella</taxonomicName>
, but flattened and often retracted as in 
<taxonomicName id="171596921143A7801EECC8B2EC82654E" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Phthiracarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phthiracarus</taxonomicName>
. It differs f rom the last-mentioned genus by the prominent and erect interlamellar hairs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="32947840386BA87FCC175A5CD7F7F2C9" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="63455BE0AFB79D531D185F068C619B6B" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Some species of the genus, among which 
<taxonomicName id="E7A996343C3178C884CD59CA8A91D75B" authority="Michael, 1898" authorityName="Michael" authorityYear="1898" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Hoploderma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histricinum">Hoploderma histricinum</taxonomicName>
(the type), strongly remind of 
<taxonomicName id="302006742E6BA3EE0FE178D5D639CF79" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Steganacarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Steganacarus</taxonomicName>
because of the structure of the tegument. Possibly 
<taxonomicName id="CD492E8A82CDB4831E9A126EF48625DC" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Hoplophthiracarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hoplophthiracarus</taxonomicName>
is only an artificial unit; in the present paper 
<taxonomicName id="94493CCB01FEC3DCE6EB1485255BF791" authority="C.L.Koch, 1836" authorityName="C.L.Koch" authorityYear="1836" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Hoplophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variolosa">Hoplophora variolosa Berlese</taxonomicName>
is also contributed to it.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
